  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    IT architectures provide an excellent source of material for the development of training course. Training may be&#xD;
    focused on overviews of the system (e.g. an enterprise overview) or on detailed technical specifics aimed at developers&#xD;
    or maintainers.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Training_Course&quot; name=&quot;XE_Training_Course&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Each course has a defined target audience (and scope) with training provided on the required skills and knowledge for&#xD;
    this target audience.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
  <purpose>&lt;p>&#xD;
    The training course provides instruction to a target audience on the defined IT architecture, which may be at the&#xD;
    enterprise level (EA) or an IT architecture for a smaller system.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
  <briefOutline>&lt;p>&#xD;
    A training course typically has a number of &quot;modules&quot;, which vary in detail depending upon the specifics of the course.&#xD;
    The following is a typical structure for a training course:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Introduction&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;an overview of the course and the skills and knowledge;&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Modules&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;modules that&amp;nbsp;provide instruction on these skills and knowledge in a logical&#xD;
        sequence;&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Examples&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;examples and exercises are included in these modules or at appropriate points&#xD;
        during the course;&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;strong>Summary&lt;/strong> -&amp;nbsp;a summary module ensures that the target audience needs have been met.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&lt;br /></briefOutline>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription>
